{"title_page": "2011 Latvian Higher League", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition      = [[Latvian Higher League]]\n| season           = 2011\n| winners          = [[FK Ventspils]]\n| relegated        = [[JFK Olimps/RFS]]\n| continentalcup1  = [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n| continentalcup2  = [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]<br />[[FC Daugava|Daugava]]<br />[[Skonto FC|Skonto]]\n| continentalcup3  = [[2012\u201313 Baltic League|Baltic League]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]<br />[[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]<br />[[FC Daugava|Daugava]]<br />[[Skonto FC|Skonto]]<br />[[FC J\u016brmala]]\n| matches          = 144\n| total goals      = 453\n| league topscorer = \n| biggest home win = [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]] 7\u20131 [[JFK Olimps/RFS|Olimps/RFS]]<br />[[Skonto FC|Skonto]] 6\u20130 [[JFK Olimps/RFS|Olimps/RFS]]\n| biggest away win = [[JFK Olimps/RFS|Olimps/RFS]] 0\u20138 [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n| highest scoring  = four matches, eight goals each\n| longest wins     = 8 matches<ref name=\"LHLStats\">{{cite web |title=Virsliga - 2011 |url=http://www.whoscored.com/Regions/121/Tournaments/155/Latvia-Virsliga |work=WhoScored.com |publisher=WhoScored.com |accessdate=14 December 2011 }}</ref><br />[[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]\n| longest unbeaten = 12 matches<ref name=\"LHLStats\" /><br />[[FK Ventspils]]\n| longest winless  = 21 matches<ref name=\"LHLStats\" /><br />[[JFK Olimps|JFK Olimps/RFS]]\n| longest losses   = 21 matches<ref name=\"LHLStats\" /><br />[[JFK Olimps|JFK Olimps/RFS]]\n| prevseason       = [[2010 Latvian Higher League|2010]]\n| nextseason       = [[2012 Latvian Higher League|2012]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2011 [[Latvian Higher League]]''' ({{lang-lv|Virsl\u012bga 2011}}) was the 20th season of top-tier football in [[Latvia]]. It began on 15 April 2011 and ended on 5 November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary - Virsliga 2011 - Latvia|url=https://int.soccerway.com/national/latvia/virsliga/2011/regular-season/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe competition was won by [[FK Ventspils]], who thus qualified for the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League]]. Runners-up [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs]] and third-placed sides [[FC Daugava|Daugava Daugavpils]] earned spots for the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League]]. On the bottom end of the table, [[JFK Olimps/RFS]] were relegated after losing their play-off series against [[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks J\u016brmala]].\n\nAll nine clubs played every other club four times during the course of the season: twice at home and twice away. In addition, there will be no direct relegation to the [[Latvian First League]] this year.<ref name=ClubMeeting>{{cite web|title=Virsl\u012bgas \u010dempion\u0101ta klubu un LFF san\u0101ksmes l\u0113mumi|url=http://www.lff.lv/lv/news/2011/jan/84/|publisher=[[Latvian Football Federation]]|accessdate=17 February 2011|language=Latvian}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n[[FK Jaun\u012bba R\u012bga|Jaun\u012bba R\u012bga]] finished [[2010 Latvian Higher League|the previous year]]'s competition in tenth place and were relegated to the Latvian First League. This ended a one-year stay in the top flight. Promoted to the Higher League from the First Division automatically were the previous season's First Division champions, [[FB Gulbene 2005|Gulbene 2005]], who are taking part in the top flight for the first time in their history in 2011.\n\n[[FC Tranzit]] finished 9th in the 2010 Higher League competition and were supposed to compete in a promotion/relegation playoff against the runners-up of the First Division, [[FC J\u016brmala]]. However, before this playoff took place, Tranzit informed the [[Latvian Football Federation]] that they were forfeiting their place in the Higher League altogether, ending a two-year stay in the top flight.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} Therefore, FC J\u016brmala were promoted to the Higher League automatically. Like Gulbene, they are competing in the top flight for the first time in their history in 2011.\n\nFinally, [[SK Bl\u0101zma]] decided to withdraw from the league during the off-season. This ended a three-year stay in the top flight. At a meeting on 28 January 2011, the LFF decided that they would not be replaced in this year's competition.<ref name=\"ClubMeeting\" />\n\n===Team summaries===\n{{Location map+|Latvia|float=right|width=350|caption=Location of teams in the '''2011 Latvian Higher League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=57.166667|long=26.75|label=[[FB Gulbene 2005|Gulbene]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=57.416667|long=21.533333|label=[[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=24.133333|label=[[Olimps/RFS]]<br>[[Skonto FC|Skonto]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.516667|long=21|label=[[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=23.75|label=[[FK J\u016brmala-VV|J\u016brmala-VV]]<br>[[FC J\u016brmala]]|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.65|long=23.716667|label=[[FK Jelgava|Jelgava]]|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=55.883333|long=26.533333|label=[[FC Daugava|Daugava]]|position=left}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Club\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n! Current manager\n|-\n|{{sort|Daugava Daugavpils|[[FC Daugava]]}}\n|[[Daugavpils]]\n|[[Daugava Stadium (Daugavpils)|Daugava Stadium]]\n|4,500\n|{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Leonid Nazarenko]]\n|-\n|{{sort|Gulbene|[[FB Gulbene 2005|Gulbene 2005]]}}\n|[[Gulbene]]\n|[[Gulbenes SC]]\n|1,500\n|{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Mihails Ko\u0146evs]]\n|-\n|{{sort|Jelgava|[[FK Jelgava]]}}\n|[[Jelgava]]\n|[[Zemgales Olimpiskais Sporta Centrs]]\n|2,200\n|{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Dainis Kazakevi\u010ds]]\n|-\n|{{sort|Jurmala|[[FC J\u016brmala]]}}